author: Engineer6

title: FreeCAD GCode import for Slic3r and Skeinforge

description.text:
FreeCAD GCode import Python module.
Imports 3D GCode from Slic3r and Skeinforge (RepRap) as groups (layers) and 3D wires (polylines) in FreeCAD document.
In FreeCAD you have the full power of a CAD application to visualize the generated pathways.
FreeCAD can import and export a lot of common file formats, including .STL format.

FreeCAD is a general purpose Open Source 3D CAD/MCAD/CAx/CAE/PLM modeler, aimed directly at mechanical engineering and product design but also fits a wider range of uses in engineering, such as architecture or other engineering specialties. FreeCAD web site:
http://sourceforge.net/apps/mediawiki/free-cad/index.php?title=Main_Page Installation: 1) Install latest version of FreeCAD (version 0.12).
2) Download the GCode.zip file from this page.
3) Unpack and copy files to ../FreeCAD0.12/Mod/GCode directory.
4) Start FreeCAD and choose File->Open to open *.gcode files. Extruding moves is shown in dark and non extruding in light grey. Each group (layer) is named Layer_xxxx, where xxxx is the extruding height in 1/100 mm. To see individual extruding layers (groups) use the toggle/hide/show visibility option in Edit->Visibility sub menu. This GCode import filter has been inspired by the Blender addon found at: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6236 The GCode import filter is written in Phyton (http://python.org/) from ground up as a learning exercise (Python is new to me :).

remixed_from.author: dintid
remixed_from.title: Flat Filament Spool Holder - No spring- The Claw remake

description.text:
Ultra Flat Filamentholder

I redid my old Flat Filament Spool Holder in Autodesk Fusion 360 (completely free for private and small business -users) and made it 8mm lower. Improved accuracy, print time, and did a general touch up.

You can view it in 3D on Autodesk360 hub.
Hope you like it.

Usage

  • Mount on the rear/side or inside your printer case...On your wall or in cabinets etc etc.
  • The numbers in the filenames are indicates how many times you need that specific part printed.

Extras

I've added some Slider Mounts Extender and Slider Mounts Short Extender in case you have special needs.
I use the extender parts to be able to use big 2.3kg rolls, but also use the same setup for smaller standard rolls.

BOM

  • 6x F688 bearings - METRIC: 8mm (Inner) x 16mm (Outer) x 5mm (Width)
  • 2x m3 lock nuts - nylon.
  • 2x m3 heat set or press fit nuts
  • 4x m3 20mm screws
  • + screws/nuts to mount the parts to the surface of your choice

Printer:

My Crossbot design

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2-0.25

Infill:

25-55

Notes:

Print Settings Used

  • I printed using a 0.4mm nozzle.
  • 3 perimeters/borders
  • 3 top and bottom.
  • Mount Point 25% infill
  • Slider Mounts 25%
  • Slider Release 44%
  • Rollers 55%
  • Spacer...

Support

  • Only need support when printing the Slider Mounts/Extender. Set Support overhang Angle to 85% to avoid support in recesses for the nuts.
  • I did not need to use support on Rollers or any other parts than Slider Mounts

Minor cleaning of parts and inserttion of nuts and bearings.

The parts doesn't require a lot of post-processing.

  • Just clean up any stringing you might have.
  • Insert the m3 nuts where needed, using a longer m3 screw to haul them in.
  • Insert 2 F688 bearings for each roller

This is a remake of my Flat Filament Spool Holder

I decided to redesign everything in Autodesk Fusion 360 as I needed some changes done.

Major changes:

  • The entire assembly is 8mm lower.
  • Using m3 inserts for the Release Trap of the Slider part.
  • Rollers print without support. Can print 4 in a bit over an hour, where 1 took 44 minutes before!
  • All parts are more accurate.

The fingernut is from Ultimate Nut Knob Generator and is named Fingernut_M3x10_v1_1.stl

description.header: m3 heat or press fit nut
description.text: Insert your heat set or press fit m3 nut. I used a heat set version, but inserted it using a plier.

Screw on m3 lock-nut on a m3 20mm screw. Insert into the fingernut and assembly it as shown. Lines on print is due to 2 walls only. More info

If you need additional info on how to mount or use this please take a look at my previous version Flat Filament Spool Holder - No spring- The Claw remake where I added a lot more information.

How it works: There are 2 Flanged bearings in each of the rollers, which ensures very smooth motion with no risk of any wheel tightening up.

title: Ducted Micro Frame
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A ducted micro quadcopter frame - the big brother of the tiny whoop!
I designed this to be a replacement frame for the QX90, but it can easily be built using individually sourced parts.
AUW with the configuration I've got is only 54g, exact same as the stock QX90!
Complete QX90: http://bit.ly/2dkGEGp

Part List:

  • Flight Controller: http://bit.ly/2cuV9RC
  • Receiver: http://bit.ly/2dkvvRq
  • Cam/VTX: http://bit.ly/2cDRCUB
  • Motors: http://bit.ly/2cuWJ5Z
  • Props: http://bit.ly/2dkve0A
  • Batteries I use: http://bit.ly/2db32MX (Battery clip is designed to fit these. They won't fit over the stock packs)

28/09/2016 - Added version for 7mm motors.
24/10/2016 - Added version with thicker motor supports.
25/10/2016 - Added revision V0.5. Slightly thicker motor supports and added hooks for mounting battery via rubber band.
27/10/2016 - Fixed and added durable version of revision V0.5
28/10/2016 - Added revision V0.5.1. Fixed minor dimensional errors

Notes:

Design is optimised for 0.4mm extrusion width.

Motor holes are designed to have an interference fit of ~0.3-0.5mm for a solid grip. The press tool goes on top of motor hole and then the motor placed at the bottom of the hole. This is then pressed together in a vise (motor shaft passes through small hole in the press tool) until the top of the motor is flush with the top of the motor hole.

8.0, 8.5, and 9.0mm motor hole models are included incase tolerances are too tight for your printer or you want to glue the motors.
~ From community feedback it seems that the 9mm model is best suited for the 8.5mm motors ~

comments.author: Quint

comments.text:
I use SImplify3D.
The duct walls are 1mm thick so you need to make sure your slicer is generating 2 perimeters for the walls (no infill). It has been a long time since I've used cura or slic3r but I'd imagine there is an extrusion width setting. Play with that until your slicer is generating the 2 perimeters all the way around. 0.4-0.5mm should be the best.

description.text:
I'm a big fan of bollards, and tend to look for them whenever I'm out and about. This model represents a typical bollard, usually a metal or plastic sleeve around a concrete pillar.

This bollard is designed to sit on your desk on a 2x2 cm plate and is just under 4.5 cm tall.

Designed in Autodesk Fusion 360. There are lots of kinds of bollards, but this is a pretty typical plated bollard and adapts well to something that can stand on its own. The interior is hollow to reduce material cost.

title: Quick start script for FlashForge Creator Pro left extruder

description.text:
Like? :-D
If this thing made your day better, please click the Like button above. Thank you!
Feel free to PM me if you have any feedback or questions. -CK

==============================================
For those of us who don't like to wait!
Please ignore the .stl file - it's just workaround for Thingiverse requiring a model to upload

Leveling:
Maximize your print quality by leveling first! I use my 3 square print:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1776032

To use:

  • See image above
  • In Simplify3D, if you're setup to use the left extruder only, go to your Process menu -> Settings tab
  • In the "Starting Script" tab, select all the text shown and save it to a backup text file
  • Replace all that text in the "Starting Script" tab with the text in my file
  • Done!

I recommend preheating your bed and extruder using the buttons and menus on the printer before starting your print. This will save you a ridiculous amount of time, allowing both to heat at the same time, as opposed to a start-up script which heats one first then the other (as is the linear nature of gcode).

Highlights:

  • Left extruder only!
  • Runs Z-homing at 50% speed (50mm/min) for a more accurate level
  • Rapidly moves to front of bed @ 9000mm/min!
  • Fast blob (less than 1s!)
  • Rapidly moves to start position @ 3000 mm/min

Go forth and print faster!

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text:
As some have noticed, the seat on the Versys is tilted forwards just a little bit too much. There are a few remedies for this, from a new seat cover, to using piles of washers to lift the front end of the stock seat. I have come up with what I think, is a low cost yet elegant solution: A 3D printed Riser Block!

As you can see, it lifts the front of the seat up just a little bit (12mm) to give you a much more comfortable ride. I have about 600+ miles on my riser block and it has been holding up great.

description.text:
A ring-rope of string-ring puzzle. One should release the ring without (of course!) cutting the rope. I found a similar puzzle under the name "Pillar and ring puzzle", which has the same solution as the one here. If you can't find it yourself the instructions are easily found on the internet.

The puzzle can be printed using one STL-file. Maybe you need supports for the little balls. Otherwise one can use the separate STL-files to print each of the components seperately (1 thing, 1 ring, 2 boxes and 2 balls is a complete set). The SCAD-file is included as well and allows to change the dimensions of the puzzle. Note that the size of the elements all depend on the inner and outer diameter of the ring, otherwise the puzzle cannot be solved.

After printing I used a drill to clean the holes from any printing irregularities. The rope can be of any length, but the free end between the two boxes should be at least three ring diameters. I used electricity wire, because it has the right diameter and I could easily fix the ends by using some solder.

description.text:
Build Album
https://goo.gl/photos/dA3D3UkkQjNfr7hH6

Ultimetal

(V2 coming soon with a range of improvements)

A Printer with a large print volume, rigid metal lasercut chassis,fast motion platform and dual extruder's.

Whats Available:
Full Model .STEP
Lasercut .dxf files
Prototype BOM (Bom used to build prototype use only for reference make your own
from parts list since pricing and parts availability depends on your
region)
Parts and Quantity List
STL Files
More to come such as schematics, wiring diagrams and instructions.

Quick Specifications:
Print Volume: 280mm x 290mm x 320mm (x,y,z)
Print Speed: Up to 200mm/s (Dependent on the User)
Hotend temp: Max <300 Celsius
Heatbed temp 100 Celsius (Possible Higher - Not yet tested)
XY Precision: 10 Micron
Minimum Layer Height: 50 Microns
Leadscrew Precision: 100 Micron deviation per 300mm
Hotend: E3D Chimera
Stepper Motor: Nema 17 1705HS200A 2-AMP 1.8-Step 0.8Nm
(Any Nema 17 motor mounting compatible)

Controller Board: Rumba Board
(Mounting possible for any controller with a suitable 3d printed mount-
An array of mounting holes are available on the chassis)
Extruders: Easy to use extruders with easy access to the hobbedgear
Hobbed Gear: Mk8
Belt: GT2 6mm Wide
Chassis: Lasercut - CR4 Steel Primed and Spray Coated with Acrylic Matte Black Paint
(Mounting hole array at back of chassis and electronics mounting plate for
easy mounting of components of your choice)
Clear Panels: Clear Laser-cut Acrylic (Future Upgrade)
Heatbed: 3mm Borosilicate 300mm x 300mm with 12v Silicon 300w Heatbed
( Standard Mounting holes available for 200x200mm,200x300mm,300x300mm
sized pcd heatbeds)
Heatbed Relay: Celduc somo-40100 Solid State Relay (60V 40AMP MAX DC-DC)
Heatbed Wiring: 12 Gauge Copper Wire
Power Supply: Corsair CX750 (Any standard ATX format power supply can be mounted
to the chassis)
Display Controller: Full Graphic Smart Controller
Controller Firmware: Marlin (Ultimetal modified marlin available on this page to download)
Pulley: 32 Tooth

(More specification details will be added soon)

This printer was developed as a project for my college to build a printer for printing
large models for a research institute. They wanted the capability to use multi materials,
hence the use of a E3D chimera.

A Cartesian XYZ motion similar to the ultimaker 3d printer is used. This lowers the mass of the moving xy gantry. A bowden system is used to lower the mass further. But extra calibration is required for the bowden system. Lower mass also means that corner definition is improved and faster accelerations and deceleration's are improved.

The steel chassis makes this machine incredible rigid and heavy. If your building it you could lasercut it in aluminium to lower the weight. Heavy is a good thing since it helps lower the resonance and vibration of the machine. The lasercut plates slot into each other and then bolted together.

I designed the extruder to be easy to access the filament drive gear. The end of the stepper shaft is supported at the end to decrease the deflection. Pneumatic coupler's are on both end of the extruder to allows ptfe tubing to and from the extruder. The ptfe tube is
in close proximity to the drive gear. Making it easier to print in flexible filaments although
i have not tested this yet.

Any controller can be mounted to the chassis provided you design a mounting plate for the controller. The electronic plate has an array of holes 40mm distance apart. If you feel
that any other controller suits your need better no problem. But be sure that is can support 2x Extruder Stepper + 2 Z Stepper + 1 X Stepper + 1 Y Stepper = 6 Steppers.
I have designed mounting and fan system for the rumba controller.

The full graphic display is used for the display. There is no option to change this unless the front lasercut plate is redesigned which is possible. There is a slot at the side for easy access to use an SD card.

Lasercut clear plates .dxf files are available. I haven't added this feature to the printer.
A magnetic latching handle has been designed for the front panel. This feature will
only work for ferrous metals. The printer was originally designed with no clear panels.
So no mounting holes for them on the chassis for now.

A solidstate relay is used to switch the headbed power. I was originally going to use a circuit i have developed myself. But i decided that it was worth the extra cost of getting
a reliable of the shelf component.

The heatbed heating unit is a silicon heat matt stuck to the 3mm Thich Borosilicate glass
sheet. The silicon mat was applied to the glass using a double sided thermal tape. 12 Gauge copper speaker wire was used to supply the high current.

Printer:

P3STEEL

No

No

Resolution:

0.2MM

Infill:

20%

PETG Used for all Printed Parts

comments.text: Pretty nice looking.  One question however.  If you are going through the trouble to redesign something to improve on it, why would you bother using standard acme lead screws and nuts for the Z?  Why wouldnt you go ahead and use ball screws?  They arent that expensive anymore for decent ones.
comments.author: The_Wizard

comments.text: Ballscrew doesn't really offer any advantage when it comes to the task of moving the z in the case of this printer since backlash isn't a problem since the mass of gantry keeps the leadscrew nut down and it moves relatively slowly. The leadscrews used are relatively high quality. I have been getting 50 micron layer height no problem. High quality ballscrew can cost significantly more then high quality leadscrews. Google the: the engineers guide leadscrews vs ballscrews .The first link will have a PDF explaining the pros and cons.

Reveal the hidden IR spectrum world with a RGB filter. Sky turns red, black clothes and hair look blue, flowers glow in the light blue bushes and a whole lot other neat stuff :) 
The way this works is that the negatives create pictures by blocking the red, green, blue colors and when you stack a whole bunch of fully exposed films together, only other wavelengths go thru. And when camera\'s sensor can detect (and show) IR light, you\'ll get pictures exposed with only infrared light.
(I first saw this in a HackaDays article years ago but in that they also removed IRfilter from the sensor. I haven't done that so exposure times are measured in seconds -> CHDK comes handy)

For this you\'ll need 4-7 picture size fully exposed developed negatives (those black ones at the end of the negative strips) and a negative size piece of plexi/polycarbonate glass. Simply sandwitch the negatives and plexi between the housing and the lid. Note: This is designed for Ixus700 and for its 26mm diameter barrel.
If you have newer camera with smaller barrel, there is housing.stl file with no hole punched in the Zip file so that you can cut better fitting hole for your camera.

description.text:
Disengaging the feeder lever on the Ultimaker2+ can be a bit of a pain, on your fingers mostly. This is a slightly re-designed lever that is longer and has a "jammer" that you can slide into feeder to lock the lever in place so you can feed in or remove filament easily.

A word of warning, your original lever might be glued together. This will make it very difficult to take apart without breaking it. If you do break it you obviously void your warranty.

I suggest printing it solid for strength and I also used CPE+ for some extra heat resistance. You might also want to consider glueing the two halves together. I haven't put a whole lot of print time on mine yet (only 50-60 hours) so I don't know if it'll split apart at the seam.

title: Bed Level Correction Calibration Squares
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
The Original Prusa MK2 has a "Bed Level Correction" calibration setting where one can virtually set the nozzle on Left/Right/Front/Back sides to correct for minor differences in first layer up to 50 microns. This is a .2 high print so only one layer will be printed with a .15 initial layer.

To use, I print out initially where one square is perfect (by adjusting Live Adjust Z calibration). Then I check the opposite square and saw the separation between filament lines. It could be ripped easily indicating not enough squish. In the calibration settings I virtually lowered the nozzle by 15 microns (-.15). Eventually I was able to determine that with a left side bed level correction set to -.35 all 4 outer squares (and center square) printed with an equal squish. Further Live Adjust Z will set all sides equally going forward.

title: Level your bed live! Levelling squares + Tutorial

description.text:
Like? :-D
If this tutorial helped you, please click the Like button above. Thank you!
Feel free to PM me if you have any feedback or questions. -CK

==============================================
I designed this method and model when I did high production printing with a farm of Flashforge Creator Pros. It's super reliable and very rewarding. Start-to-finish should take you less than 20 minutes the first time. I do it in under 5 now.

Features

  • More than just levelling
    • Makes your top and bottom surface finish beautiful
    • Guarantees bed adhesion and layer-to-layer adhesion across your bed
    • Level can last 3 weeks and longer (depending on how you treat your bed)
    • Gives you the perfect balance of great bed adhesion and easy part removal
  • 50 x 50 x 0.6 mm squares
  • Squares are centered over the levelling screws
  • Concepts work for any number of extruder heads
  • See my recommendations for print settings way at the bottom!
  • Designed for 0.40mm nozzle, 0.2mm layer height, and itprints at 40mm/s

Recommended Tools

  • toothbrush
  • 0.10 mm feeler gauge
  • flashlight
  • 2" chisel (use it upside-down, and be gentle!)

How to Level
This file is specifically designed for 3-point levelling on a FF Creator Pro, but if it helps you then that's awesome!

1. Clean the nozzles

  • Preheat both extruders above the melting points of your filaments
  • Turn off the extruder heaters. As they cool, brush them off with the toothbrush. This prevents blobs from remaining and confusing your level.

2. "Rough" level

  • Home the bed
  • Lower your bed so there is a visible gap under the nozzles
  • Jog the carriage to align the right nozzle over the back-right screw
  • Use the feeler gauge to bring the bed up to the nozzle. You'll feel the gauge vibrate and possibly get stuck, so back off the screw until the moment you don't feel the gauge vibrate
  • Repeat for the left extruder over the left screw.
  • Jog the carriage to align it's middle over the front screw
  • Bring up the bed slowly, checking both nozzles
  • If one nozzle touches first, jog to the back screws and re-level them
  • A couple of iterations should get your bed printable

3. Fine tuning
AKA tuning on-the-fly!

  • Load the model into Simplify3D (or skip ahead and just use the .x3g)
    • Left extruder, 0.2mm: level squares L0.2.x3g
    • Right extruder, 0.2mm: level squares R0.2.x3g
  • If needed, load the attached printing profile and modify your Machine Definition or material-specific settings.
  • Preheat the bed and the extruder you want to level (see my recommendations at the bottom!)
  • Start the print!
  • 2 outlines are printed first. There is no skirt outline, so it might take a couple seconds to get adhesion
    • If filament isn't laying down, bring your bed up while printing
    • If nothing is coming out, back off!
    • The ideal bead adheres, but and is twice as wide as it is high
      Now for the printer fu!
  • Your bed is going to be tilted from parallel (to your nozzles). Pivoting happens rotationally about the axis between screws. That means if you move one screw, the bed pivots from the other two.
  • Use your flashlight. Shine it across the peaks between lines
    • If there are shadows, move the bed away at that screw, but only small fractions of a turn
    • If there are no shadows, shine the light along the bead lines. If you see gaps, move the bed closer
    • Tilt is observed as "spluging out" on one side of the nozzle, as if it's too close on one side of the nozzle, and too far away on the other side (spluges go "up-hill"). See the above drawing. That means you have to raise 1 screw and lower 2 screws, just barely
  • Do these 3 things iteratively until your top layer is so smooth you can see the reflection of the nozzle on it. See the image above - it's a beautiful thing :-)

CAUTION
Roughly handling your bed - such as pushing down on it, forefully removing parts, or yanking on it in any way - will ruin your level. Be gentle! Treat the bed as a delicate piece of china, a precision system. That's what will make your level last.

Material-Specific Recommendations
These settings just work. This is for medium-quality printing, not high-res or super-fast.

  • PLA
    • Bed: 55C, preheat to 55C
    • Ext: 220C, preheat to 225C
    • Speed: 50mm/s (3000mm/min)
    • Active fan: 100% @ layer 1, if you have one
  • ABS
    • Bed: 100C, preheat to 100C
    • Ext: 235C, preheat to 238C
    • Speed: 50mm/s (3000mm/min)
    • Active fan: Not necessary, hasn't helped me

General Filament Recommendations
Applies to plastic like PLA and ABS

  • Layer Height: 0.200mm
  • Multiplier: 1.00, if you're changing this value you are doing something else wrong
  • Speeds:
    • Outline: 60%
    • Solid Infill: 80%
    • Support: 60%
    • X/Y: 100mm/s (6000mm/min)
    • Z: 20mm/s (1800mm/min)
    • Bridging: 130% extrusion, 75% speed

title: OOML - C++ Object Oriented Mechanics Library

description.text:
Have you ever used OpenSCAD, great, isn't it? Now, imagine that you are not anymore limited by the OpenSCAD syntax and libraries. Imagine using recursion to create objects, inheriting some parts from others, having at your disposal hundreds of geometry libraries, and much moreâ€¦ that's the OOML. The OOML is simply a C++ empowered OpenSCAD.
OOML stands for Object Oriented Mechanics Library. The OOML is a set of tools written in C++ that allow designers to create mechanical parts using the C++ language.
OOML applies the model of Object Oriented Programming to Mechanical Designs. Parts can be inherited from others. A part can join together other existing parts, and so forth.
OOML has up to now no external dependency and can be used in any computer having a standard C++ compiler.
Up to current version OOML generates OpenSCAD code. Using OpenSCAD designers may generate the STL of the parts.
OOML is Open Source, you can use it, modify it, share it.
OOML brings together both the design of pieces through code (as it's done with OpenSCAD) with the programming power of an Object Oriented Language as C++.
OOML provides a powerful tool for designers to boost their creativity building mechanical parts. As it uses C++, designers may use any other existing C++ library to calculate, manipulate, create their parts.
OOML allow designers to create and share their own Parts Libraries, which will certainly enrich the community.

You have all the source code, documentation, tutorials, examples, etc at http://iearobotics.com/oomlwiki The OOML has been tested on Linux, Mac OS/X and Ms Windows. On the figures you can see examples of implemented OOML parts, ready to use, modify, inherit, etc. The following people have participated in the OOML programming and testing:

I saw an image that showed something of the sort. It inspired me to create a 3d printable version. The image/s that I got the inspiration from are the first image, and last few images shown.

This wall decoration key holder has several files:
HoneyCombWallSingle - This file is a single wall cell.
HoneyCombKeyChain -This file is what you attach your keys to
HoneyCombWall - This file is a random arrangement of multiple Honeycomb cells.
HoneyCombNailPeg - This file is the peg that you insert into the blank hole after nailing the cells to the wall.

I used the dimensions of a common nail I had lying around. Its length from point-head is about 38mm. The shank diameter is about 1.6mm, and the head diameter is about 4.0mm. I recommend using the highest resolution your printer allows, to make sure the nail holes are precise/accurate.

If you have a better way of attaching it to the wall, please tell me or make a remix of it.

title: Desk Lamp "The Arc" cnc/laser
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Like the Dimmable Night Light this desk lamp is lit by the small and economical Ledberg Spotlight from IKEA. The construction allows for a pretty wide reach. In this case you need to weight the foot with some heavy stuff. I did use an iron bar I found in my workshop. To get the switch in a good position I removed the plastic cover from the switch and milled a applicable pocket.

My build was done from 6,5 mm beech plywood and some 4 mm high density fiber using a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft. The 'arm' needs to be cut twice from the high density fiber.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs. Consider a donation if you like the build.

title: Wargaming Line of Sight Periscope
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I wanted to better be able to tell line of site when playing 15mm scale war games. I bought a bag of 25mm round mirrors and threw this design together. You may need to modify it for your uses depending on the size of your print bed and the size of your mirrors.

You'll need to glue the mirrors in some how to keep them in the slots after you slide them in. I plan on using a small bit of filament glued in the slot as the slot is a touch over 2mm and filament is 1.75 that should work out ok.

Do not use super glue as that tends to leave a white fog on the mirrors.

This is a bracket that I use for my DIY solar array setup. It allows the array to fold up nicely for transport. It's parameterized and written in Open SCAD, so using arbitrarily sized panels is just matter of entering their size.

To customize, open in Customizer and change the "X" and "Y" parameters. You can probably ignore the rest (There seems to be a bug in Customizer and it's not hiding the other parameters).

A dab of hot glue on each corner attaches the panel to the bracket. I attach the brackets together by running fabric underneath along the length. I chose this over using hinges since I felt like the hinges added bulk, failure points, and the canvas protects the wiring and contacts underneath. Plus it looks kind of cool!

I wrote up some info on it here: http://www.safetyoptional.com/2016/09/diy-solar/

remixed_from.author: Ellindsey
remixed_from.title: TOM build platform cable management system

description.text: I printed Ellindsey's TOM build platform cable management system (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16069), because I wanted better strain relied than I had been using. Unfortunately, I found two problems. First, the cable from the HBP would not reach the side of the Y axis and back to the front right corner of my TOM. Second, I had already added MakeALot's Linear Bearing X Axis Carriage for ToM (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9420), so there were no vertical ribs to attach the x stage mount to. So, I used OpenSCAD to generate a few new parts to make the system work on my TOM.

If your cable is too short, print the cable_guide_t_link.stl.
If your build platform no longer has vertical ribs, print the cable_guide_x_stage_anchor_90.stl. To use the t-link, put the cable management system together as described in the original thing, but without running the heater wires back to the midpoint. Instead, find the spot where the links going from the base to the midpoint are approximately the same height as the build platform and replace a couple of links with the t-link. Make certain the T is oriented towards the center of the front of the TOM. Now run the links from the build platform to the T this should still move nicely without kinking the cables (or trying to pull them out of the base). To use the rotated x-stage anchor, follow the directions in the original thing, except you will want to mount it on the bottom horizontal wood plate of the HBP instead of on the rib. The spacing here is a little tight, so I would suggest using one of the low-profile M3 screws instead of a normal M3 screw. Connect the linkage to the anchor and you should have reasonable strain relief.

title: Geeetech i3 PRO B E3D extruder holder

description.text:
Cheap upgrade for geeetech i3 pro B printer that improves printing performance.
I used clone E3D V6 from aliexpress.com
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/3D-Printer-J-head-Hotend-with-Fan-for-1-75-3-0mm-12-v-E3D-v6/32371544116.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.123.MVTJm3
Just write down seller to send you 0,4mm nozzle and for 1,75mm filament.
For LED light I used 60mm LED ring from banggood.com
http://www.banggood.com/A-pair-of-60mm-White-15-LED-SMD-Car-Angel-Eyes-HeadLight-Halo-Ring-Lights-p-994533.html
First I cut some pcb from ring. But be careful not to destroy lines, resistor or LED. See photo where I marked cutting line.
At the end just solder hotend fan and LED ring wires together and connect to extruder fan connector on GT2560 board.

Printer:

GEEETech I3 PRO B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0,2mm

Infill:

35%

Notes:

Just print all parts at once.
Put them close as possible and use brim (20 lines) for perfect print.
I used CURA 2.1.2 for slicing parts and preparing code.

First remove all brim and support from printed parts.
Use 3mm drill bit for all holes to make them exactly 3mm diameter. Then use M3 anti loosening nuts and insert them in hexagon holes. For attaching hotend use M3x30mm screws , for attaching holder, use 1x M3x6mm and 2x M3x10mm screws. All screws can be found in 3D printer kit (they put a lot of spare screws, nuts and washers).
For attaching LED ring use thin double side tape and 2x M3x6 or M3x10 screws for attaching holder to metal plate.

title: Geeetech prusa i3 pro B z-axis top mounts

description.text:
along with making my own anti-z-wobble design and successfully installing and using it, I drilled out the original z-axis top mount lead screw hole (to allow the lead screw to move more freely but also as the holes on my acrylic were to small and were actually causing the lead screw to bind)

though the Z-axis wobble now vanished I had to now put up with the lead screw jiggling about which if Im honest was annoying the crap out of me (specially when the printer is returning to home position and the lead screw bounces about like crazy (tbh I cant see it being to healthy for the already bent screw and the coupling either)

so after a quick look round thingiverse for what I wanted I couldnt find anything that really suited my needs (I wanted something simple, original looking and fitted in with what was already in place), again everything seemed a tad over engineered for my tastes.

all I wanted was something as close to similar to the original top mount as I could get with the facility to except a loose fitted bearing to stabilize the 8mm lead screw, it didnt need to be a solid fitted bearing and it didnt need to be supportive, just act as a guide to stop the lead screw flying all over the place.

couldnt find anything so again started from scratch.

heres my almost identical to original top mount design with a adaptions made to except a loose fitting F608ZZ 8mm bearing.

must say, works a treat..... even if I do say so myself

Printer:

Geeetech Prusa i3 pro B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

30%

Notes:

this design works best with a Z-Axis anti-wobble mod (or "floating z-axis") which helps eliminate any effect created by minor distorted z-axis lead screws.

I use it with my own design and has so far proven perfectly effective in eliminating any and all z-axis wobble effects.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1775786

title: Hotend fan duct for prusa i3

description.text:
This hotend fan duct is for a specific Prusa i3 variant - ANet A8.

The original kit came with a standard 40mm blower fan. It was ok for a lot of cases but couldn't get sufficient air moving when I wanted faster cooling for difficult shapes.

I replaced it with a much stronger 60mm fan. Also I built this duct so that the air will flow in different directions. It solves the problem that material on the side opposite to the fan didn't get enough cooling power.

Designed and printed 2 slightly different designs. Both seem to work equally well. The designs are available at OnShape here so that anyone can customize it to your needs.

Printer Brand:

title: Quadcopter landing gear 1306 motor 12mm hole pattern

description.text:
These are bolt-on landing gear for a 130mm or larger quad using 1306 motors (or any motor with a 12mm mounting hole pattern). They add enough height below the chassis to strap an 850mAh 3s battery onto the bottom of the quad. Stretch them in the Z direction if you need more height...

As printed, the gear are too weak to use. They tend to break off below the ball in a crash.

To make them much stronger, ream out the center hole with a 1mm drill bit (or a #60) and glue in a section of 1mm carbon fiber rod.

Mendelmax 1.5

Rafts:

No

No

0.2

Notes:

DIY Tattoogun, made ozt of three 3D printed pieces, a motor (mine is from an old Playstation Controller), with a piece to offset the driveshaft, and a little pin to attach the neadle to.

Those 3 pieces are glued together. Mine are made out of ABS, so I just use aceton to glue them together.

Because my motor is an old Playstation controller rumble motor, it allready had a little metal piece attached to it, where I just drilled a 2mm hole, to glue in a little pin.

The neadle is made out of a thin metall wire, which is bend into a loop at one end and sharpened on the other end with a dremel tool and some files.

This Tattoogun is made to tattoo leather and other nonliving objects and not to use on a human or other creatures!

My Motor is simply hooked up to a 12V power supply

27.11.2016
As my E3D after some time started to move a little bit, I decided to add 2 3 mm holes and a mount piece that would hold the connecting part of the E3D pretty tight in there .
The only downfall is that you need to add really long 3 mm bolts, I have some but they are not so common .
Better solution would be to not go through with the holes and just add some captive nuts so that normal 30 mm bolts can be used to tighten the E3D .

I started editing this so I can mount an E3D Lite hotend, the 6 mm version with 2 mm offset on the bottom and support for the fan on the left is the latest version that fits with my other gantry, extruder etc . for the Printrbot to have a direct drive extruder and also the much shorter E3D hotend .
This is not tested yet, I am still using the original version with some shims that space properly the hotend and the extruder but I already printed the latest version and will put some photo when it is mounted .

My wife asked me to design a box with a fitted-lid and a handle of some kind, so I came up with the idea to make it kind of like a drawer turned on it's side, with a drawer-like knob.

The lid has an inset ridge to fit inside the box lip, with a chamfered screw hole to connect the knob from the underside. The holes are 0.3mm in diameter and fit any small wood screws with chamfered heads of about this size.

I should also note that there's 1mm (0.5mm on each side) of spacing between the lid ridge and the box inner-edge, to ensure some tolerance for printing/fitting. I could adjust this in the CAD project and add a perfect-fit lid model if anyone is interested.

One of the nice features of the Wemos D1 Mini ESP8266 Development board is the ability to stack "shields" onto each other to add capabilities.

Since the arrangement of the stack is up to the builder, I thought it would be easier just to have the user enter the offset for placing the "port" of a shield. Just enter a zero offset if you don't need the port.

The sample STL is for a Wemos board with a battery shield and an sd card shield.

The customizer currently support these shields:

  • Micro SD Card shield
  • Battery Power shield
  • Relay shield

description.text: Does your work bench have too much junk and too little light? This fearsome, 36-eyed task lamp puts your junk to work as ballast in the handy storage tray. It uses four of the ubiquitous 9-LED flashlights (25mm dia), each individually aim-able for broad or spot focus. The flashlights unclip easily for remote illumination. No

Notes:

You'll need to print 1 base, 1 spider, 4 clips and 4 links.

The ball and socket joints should snap together easily. Work them around until they operate smoothly. Each socket has a hole for a 3/8" long 4-40 screw (or 10mm long M3) and nut (9 total). You can adjust the clamping force on each to get just the right amount of friction to hold the lamp in position. If the ball joints are sticky or squeaky, give them a little dab of light grease or vaseline.

You'll also need four of the cheap 9-LED flashlights. I got mine at Harbor Freight (which are sometimes even free with a coupon), but any flashlight with a 25mm dia body should work.

description.text:
An adapted design of flyingferret's :
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1479176

This thing allows for real quick and precise adjustment of the Z limit switch.

The Leg screws into the X stepper through the X carriage and the slotted holes provide for larger adjustment where an M3 bolt/screw then allows for fine adjustment.

I used a thread tap to cut straight into the plastic, i'm sure a normal screw would cut its own thread in there easy enough if you apply enough force. Same applies to the little foot that screws onto the tip of the M3 bolt. The limit switch screws onto the switch mount with 2x M2 screws (which came with my printer)

Good luck!

comments.author: jschievink

comments.text: An easy way to cut threads into plastic is to make a tap out of a screw. Simply file a flat spot on the side of the screw until you get down to the shank (the un-threaded portion of the metal). Do this on one side from the tip up to the thickness you will be going into. For a 3mm screw a 2.5 mm drill should work to clear the hole for threads. Now screw the modified screw into the hole and it will cut the threads just like a tap does.
comments.author: jschievink

comments.text: I'm sorry, but it took you 3 hours to screw a screw into a hole? Even if you didn't have a drill, you didn't have any screws that were closer in size? And even if you didn't have any screws closer in size, you didn't have anything, like maybe a screwdriver that was close in size to the screws you did have, you could have heated it up on the stove and melted a larger hole and then cleaned it up with a file.

description.text:
This is a repository of the parts I made/remixed to make my large metal delta printer, the detailed build log is here http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?178,702599.

A BOM is available here:
https://1drv.ms/w/s!Apv79JfGbPIwguca-_j-QFx7E8401A

This is by no means a complete design for a printer, as it is basically a kossel.

Most of it is self explanatory.

The panel due bracket requires bonding together after assembly with superglue or acetone. In this and some other panels you might need to drill some holes to mount them with tnuts, and for cables depending on how you intend to wire yours up. Drill holes near to the push fit connectors to prevent the panels bending when the bolts are done up.

I've just uploaded the twin fan shroud, it's adjustable so you can change the side fan's height, for v6 to volcano heater block changes. There is a second version uploaded (v2-e3dv6...) which has a slightly better mounting for a dc42 IR sensor, and some spacing to allow the legs of the connector on the back of the PCB some space.

Added a panel to connect at the top front horizontal with the name of the printer which also acts as a shade if you place an LED strip facing downwards in this location. The LED shines through the text.

Added an alternative e3d v6 (and volcano its adjustable) shroud which can have a DC42 IR sensor attached to it, close to the nozzle to minimise the effect of tilt in the effector when using this sensor.

Added a revised version of the bed mounts which now have slimline clamps. My bed large and heavy though it was was moving about very slightly and throwing the bed level calculations off. If you have not made one yet make the version with the clamps and the clamps themselves and then heat press some m4 nuts into it. If you have made it already, just make the clamps, drill through them with a 4mm drill bit and then use m4 bolts and nuts heat press the nuts using the holes as a guide.

Added an adaptor which can re-orientate the magnets in a k800 style effector to 45 deg to improve holding force. Bond into the effector with superglue/epoxy, ensure spacing between magnets is the same as on the carriages.

If you want to edit most of the files you can do so:
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/k4RnvdLJWV6-large-kossel-side-panels/editv2
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1ZukNkEi8bR-bed-mounts/editv2

I have enclosed and water-cooled this machine details are at
http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?178,702599,page=8

I will add some stls specific to the enclosure or water cooling to a separate listing on Thingiverse as this one is getting a bit busy.

title: C/D-bot Anti backlash lead screw nut bracket

description.text:
This is a remix of the "2-Lead_Screw_Bracket.stl" in the D-bot by by spauda01.

This model fits the anti backlash nut from openbuild. Its important to mount the nut the correct way. As in picture.

Turn model 90 degrees before print. No support needed.

If you get the problem with the motor mount not fitting when using my design, use this: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2474608/#comments

(PS: 16.02.17: I updated the model since I found a little error in the design. The hole for the nut was 0.7mm too far from the rail. A nema 17 motor is 42 mm wide, so the correct distance from center of nut to rails are 21mm not 21.7 mm. Now fixed. Im using the old design without problems, so no need to freak out if you already printed one)

comments.text: I received these anti-backlash nuts in a kit and am not sure whether to lubricate the nut/rod since the channel is is plastic. Did you? If yes, what lubricant did you use?
comments.author: denos

comments.text: Dont think you have to use oil, but I used sewing machine oil. Only did it once when installing. Run the nut up and down a couple of times to check that the rod is smooth and get the oil spread. Dont add to much as it will drip down to buttom.

description.text:
Based on original design by gwinntanamo. Just to be clear, it's gwinntanamo's video shown here, not mine. The images are of my gun mount.

I made an improved Vive_Gun_Mount_Top (v2). The radius at the inside base of the clips is bigger. These ones should last for ages. You do hear the support snapping a little the first time you snap the pipe in, don't worry about it. It's the perimeters that have the strength.

Print in ABS.

It is suggested that the squash ball makes contact with the HMD, but for most Onward guns the contact point ends up being on your cheek or jaw. Test a few guns before you decide on a final length for your dowel. Mine is 55cm, 60cm might be better.

Designed for a 16mm oak dowel from Bunnings. Put an end cap on the butt end to protect the squash ball.

Other parts:
2x 18-20mm M3 bolt
2x M3 Nyloc nut
1x Squash ball

https://www.bunnings.com.au/porta-16mm-1-2m-tasmanian-oak-dowel_p0099409

description.text:
I love my Aeropress(es). I have 3 of them. What I don't like about the Aeropress is when I travel, I have this bag of stuff and it is easy to leave a piece behind. I would like it to assemble into a single unit for travel, as much as possible. For example, if the screen thing would have been 1mm deeper, it could attach to the press. And then there are the filters... I bet everybody has a ziplock baggie with a bunch of filters in it.

I attempt to fix both of those issues with this thing. A filter holder that attaches to the press and the screen attaches to the top of the filter holder. Filters are contained inside and kept clean. Yes!

I am still working out the fit of the lid for the filter holder. It is a little tight. I have a version that is standalone that is perfect so some of my settings may have affected this fit. Although, this is perfectly workable and may actually be desirable to have it fit very tight. I had an earlier version that had threads that I didn't like so much. I am considering adding a bayonet type latch to the lid. This part is still up for improvement. But here it is as of the moment.

The bottom portion, which I call the container, has air slots. I didn't want to trap moisture so that bacteria could grow. This also allows the plunger to be removed easily because a vacuum isn't created.

The design is public on Onshape:
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/f1d2db3903f914aefa5691ab/w/707965dd6d9bd39af46567f2/e/c684e898689edc1e65e46e97

description.text:
The mount is designed to be used with UM + or other printers with identical XY rods configuration. I use small flat stepper motor to reduce the loss of print area (Loss is in the y axis about the thickness of the motor). Because of the shorter threads in the motor, I needed to use the stepper distance modifier, few mm between the motor and the Titan so there is one attached. Although I suggest using nylon nuts because the motor becomes very warm (around 60C)

It is a fairly simple model to be used with 4 screws provided with the Titan. Upper two screws (long ones) use a distance plate which also serves to hold the wires in place. One of the lower screws goes through the bearing cylinder, so I suggest adding it before bearings are inserted. The hotend is at the same height as standard UM hotend (slight z endstop adjustment needed). Cooling shroud is included, I use the snap on like the standard V6, but added mounts for 40mm fan on both sides.

+++ IMPORTANT +++ The flat stepper motor I use is rated for 1A of power. Standard Nema 17 motor for UM extruder is much higher (up to 2A) and if not corrected, the smaller motor will overheat which will cause problems with the extruder. I reduce the motor current in Cura start gcode: M907 X1100 Y1100 Z1100 E850
Flat stepper CANNOT run reliably without heat sinks, so couple of them have been attached.

Cura Machine settings property "E-steps per 1mm filament" should be set to 350 to use with the setup. Also, retraction distance of 1.5mm with retraction speed of 25mm/sec works perfectly. Acceleration reduced from 2000 to 1500. I have added 2 12V 40mm fans in series and connected to the standard UM 19V output. It works great with minimum 40% power for them to start running.

Stepper: http://goo.gl/XeVZUk

comments.text: How the bigger weight affected to print quality? Any print pics?
comments.author: Karabas

comments.text:
Hi Karabas!
The weight didn't affect the print quality (i never go above 40mm/s). I have attached my full upgrade review pdf and Marvin 3Dhubs test print done with this setup in Copperfil (good for overhangs).
What I was not happy about is the E3D V6 and it's response to print cooling fans. It is unable to hold temperature if the air is directed below the print head to efficiently cool the exiting filament. Also, air is heated up by the heater block instead of the filament, so the efficiency drops and is not suitable for small prints (I did 2 Marvins to compensate). Ultimaker shields it's heater block with metal plating. I have since made a housing for the heater block with metal (zinc sheet) and fiberglass insulation which works wonderfully. Fans at 100% near the bed are not able to reduce the hotend temperature, instead it is stable.

title: PTFE X-axis carriage, on aluminium profile, Mmax,Prusa upgrade

description.text:
I consider it as working. I am using an "open" carriage from ABS to hold the extruder and PLA/PTFE profile mount underneath. Maybe a full PLA carriage may work, if not relaxed from hotend's heat. I changed the Y-axis also, but i have to experiment more in order to have the same results i saw with the X axis. This is the carriage for aluminium profile x axis, using this http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:171294 for the ptfe rail and simonious idler+motor holder. At Simonius profile ( http://www.thingiverse.com/Simonious/designs ) you can find the x ends for every set-up.
It's a work in progress, as the carriage won't be printed really nice, but it is working. Although i have to print with it to be sure. bare: http://youtu.be/LfLTiiDKvbU
with extruder: http://youtu.be/ERUOjpFenDY
printing: http://youtu.be/T046ZFsfEGw It is not obvious but the carriage is sagging because of the wieght of the extruder and the tolerance at the carriage's mounting. Printed with ABS, leaves some ABS dust on the profile cause of the friction. Better is to split the model and print the profile mounts out of PLA. If you make it, don't be shy. Let me know

Better wait for a better edition coming in a week or so. Otherwise
  • Print the carriage.
  • Cut the PTFE tube in the correct length.
  • Use a smaller Allen key in order to help you align the tube with the holes.

  • Screw in 4 x 3mm Allen bolts, or 8 x 3mm if you don't have lengthy enough bolts. The plastic base can hold it in place.

  • Print the desired X-ends from simonious profile.
    6.Assemble the X-ends back to printer.
  • Place carriage on aluminium profile and then on the X-ends
  • Use this endstop holder -> http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:43036

description.text: This is a calibration cube with a pattern for printing on a 2 extruder printer and fine tune the extruder offsets and other printing parameters.

There are 2 STLs. The ColorBase.stl is to be printed with one extruder the ColorPattern.stl with another. The Sketchup file has both pieces together each piece as a component. Use Skeinforge to slice. The STLs are sliced separately. Make sure both objects end up in exactly the same spot and the skirt (if used) doesn't overlap with the object. Both objects have to be slices with the same layer height. The penultimate gcode has to be generated. Pass the penultimte gcode file names for the base and the pattern to the addcolor.pl script as the first two parameters, and the names of the files with gcode for switching to the secondary extruder and back as the 3rd and 4th parameters. The merged gcode is printed to stdout (the comments are stripped and it should be ready for printing). There are more details on the mod for the printer here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16523 The pictures show the results of printing at 50mm/sec, 0.5mm nozzles.
PLA: orange/transparent(natural) and red/blue pieces
ABS: black/white(natural) The video for printing one of the ABS pieces is here:
http://youtu.be/GVVmdrmvYq8

description.text:
I edited the head in order to print the eyes in separate parts. I made a square hole in the eye in order to look like bender's eyes. I was much inspired by R3ND3R's custom eyes for the bender figure.
Add some black marker pencil in the eye pupil and the head is perfect.

you will also find the jaw part with custom supports, it is now super easy to print this part.

Also note that I scaled up the parts by 2540% in order to correct Simonarri's export in inches.

In order to make a really poseable figure :

  • use a thin metallic wire. Heat it with a lighter and insert it in the feet (same with hands and head).
    • drill a small hole in the center of the links (or make a hole with a heated wire)
    • drill and glue the other end of the wire in the firstlinks (same with hips)

Hint: if your eyes are hard to fit in the head, scale them down just a little.

have fun!

description.text:
The Modular Panel System (MPS) is a collection of files that can be used to assemble 3/4" plywood into just about any cubic shape. Currently it includes 3 files:

  • MPS - Corner Clamp - Used to hold plywood together at 90deg angles.
  • MPS - Shelf Support - Used to support flat shelving.
  • MPS - Shim - Used in conjunction with the Corner Clamp, as needed.

Complete verbose instructions for usage including print settings for each piece are on my blog:
http://www.akeric.com/blog/?p=3994

This is all common sense, but because lawyers: I am not responsible in any way for any type of accident, damage, injury, death, or cost incurred from using this system: By downloading from any source and / or making these files on any printer / fabrication system, you wave me from from any liability now or in the future. Be smart, use at your own risk, test.

You will need this additional hardware for assembly (see the attached pic):

Corner Clamp:

  • 1 Philips flat-head machine screw (or equivalent) : 1/4"-20 x 3" - K
  • 1 Hex Nut : 1/4"-20 - K
  • 2 Flat Washers : 1/4" - K

Shelf Support

  • 2 Philips Flat Head Wood Screw (or equivalent) : 10 x 3/4" - K
  • 1 Flat Washer : 1/4" - K

Notes:

I used 'MakerGeeks Raptor Series PLA' to print these brackets: it's a significantly stronger version of PLA. Much more pliable than normal, far less brittle. I would not use 'normal' PLA to print these. ABS at a minimum, but I'd highly recommend some form of Nylon, or PETG.

title: Slim Wallet with MetroCard Sliding Compartment

description.text:
I lost my wallet and was just about to head out to buy one when I reminded myself that I should just design a new one. Sure, there's a glut of slim wallets out there, but I wanted to put my own take on it. It works really well with 5-6 credit card sized items and has a separate slot made for easy access to a MetroCard which saved me from missing a train the other day. There's a little nib that clicks into the small hole toward the top of the card. Hopefully, the MTA won't change the card design any time soon. If you aren't in NYC, you can still you that slot for a picture of a loved one or yourself, if you're into that kind of thing. Blog

title: Wanhao Duplicator 6 Ball Bearing Spool Holder

description.text:
Yet another spool holder for the Wanhao D6. This uses the factory nut and threads into the same spot on the printer.

I created this as the existing bearing spool holder did not work as well as I would like. This holder has guides on the inner and outer part of the hub. I have tested it with up to 2kg spools and it works great.

Beyond the printed parts, you will need:
1x 5" long 5/16 bolt or an equivalent length of all thread
2x 608 skate bearings.
1x 5/16 nyloc nut (2x if using all thread)
1x 5/16 washer

The washer goes between the roller and the printed nut holder to act as a spacer. Just tighten the bolt enough to take up the slop but don't over tighten. If you over tighten the roller will not move smoothy.

description.text:
New, better designed, 5'16" plugs here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1790509

DISCLAIMER: I do not know how printed materials can interact. Please be sure your PLA/ABS etc will not mix or otherwise alter any vehicle fluid before using these.

This is a printable plug for fluid hoses. It was designed with automotive use in mind but is good wherever. The plug can stop hoses with an ID of 3/8" up to just below 3/4".

If there is interest I will see about creating a different grip for them but so far I have not had issues.

Note: The ones shown are not finished with post production and are not airtight yet.

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

Rostock MAX

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

40%

Notes:

I used 0.2mm layers for speed on the test prints but the better your printed product the less post production will be needed so if you are not in a hurry I would consider printing at 0.1mm. Best printed from the base straight up with a triangle or grid infill.

To get the best performance, sanding after printing should be done. I used a 120 grit paper to give it a more uniform surface. In my case, they printed being watertight but not airtight, with some quick sanding you can make these plugs as good as something molded. Start with strokes lengthwise and then wrap the sandpaper around the cone and rotate to give an even finish.

title: Rostock Max Accelerometer Board Mount for 713Maker Hotend

description.text:
This is a quick part for attaching the SeeMeCNC HE280 accelerometer board to the 713Maker hot end mount. I haven't gotten the board wired in yet, but this looks like it will do the job just fine.

The part is held on to the hot end mount with the regular bolts for it and some 8mm M3 bolts to attach the board to the part.

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

Rostock MAX

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm layer height, .4mm nozzle

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Printed in Microcenter Inland black ABS with 4 shell walls
Just some basic cleaning to make sure the holes are the proper size for the bolts to thread in without splitting the part.

comments.text:
I'm sure it holds the board in fine just threading into the plastic, but some heat-set thermoplastic inserts would be ideal for this! More solid and easier to use than a captured nut, and wont wear out if you need to remove and reinstall the board multiple times for any reason. Insert them from the bottom, with the wider side facing away from the screw head at the bottom of the hole for maximum strength, but they seem to be plenty strong threading into the top too.
Just design the part with the recommended hole size and taper, and then press it in using a soldering iron. they sell a dedicated installation tool but I havent found it to be necessary if youve got a normal iron.
https://www1.mcmaster.com/#94180a333/=15687ay
comments.author: earlynerd

comments.text: How do you like that board also? was it very difficult it get working right with the rostock? I've been considering the 713 mount and would love to also get away from having to manually calibrate my V2 so often. I'm running an E3D V6 w/pt100 sensor and wondering if its better to just get the whole HE280 upgrade kit or go with the 713maker mount and PCB only. I see the new 713maker mounts have lockrings compatible with the accel board so I probably wont need to print your part, but I'm dreading the thought of having to feed more wires down the extrusion towers though...
comments.author: earlynerd

comments.text:
I've been pretty impressed with the probe mechanism so far. I have a habit of messing with too many settings at once so it hasn't been 100% automatic for me yet. Also I hear there is a pending firmware update that might improve things. I was able to get the additional wires through the towers so I could use the whip for all the connections. Be really careful about the length of the wiring harness. The calibration routine really exercises the range of motion so it's easy for short wires to tug the connection loose.
I also have some plans for a print cooling solution that uses a variant of the mount so I haven't invested in the 713maker mount as much as I love anodized stuff.
If you are comfortable with your E3D hotend and working with the wiring and mounts, I can't think of any reason to use the full HE280 assembly over it.
comments.author: earlynerd

description.text:
This is an FPV camera mount for the Oxcart-150 quadcopter. This is a single unit (left and right sides are joined). I recommend printing upside down. You may need to provide minor bridging support in this orientation. There is also an alternative where the right and left sides are not attached.

http://www.rcgroups.com/forums/showthread.php?t=2733031

40%

Notes:

I used a single layer brim to ensure the part adhered to the bed and didn't fall over. I also used bridging support for the area that joins the two sides (I printed the part upside-down). I used a 100 micron layer height so the threads printed correctly.
